animal.description:
COSMO is a wonderful sweet boy looking for a FOSTER OR FOREVER HOME!

 Cosmo is crate trained and housebroken. He is good with other dogs and kids. No cats.  He used to walk well on leash but I’ll be honest, with Covid this year and not doing adoption events, none of the dogs have been on leashes in months. However, he’s a smart boy and learns quickly. 

Cosmo loves to play with the other dogs, play with his toys and chew on bones. He spends his days basking in the sun on the deck, playing chase or entertaining himself on his dog bed. 

His story: he came to use as a tiny pup after he was found standing in the middle of the road and no one ever claimed him. He was adorable and I thought for sure he would get adopted quickly. Nope! He grew up at the kennel house and here we are still looking for a great home. 

Neutered, microchip, fully vaccinated, and heartworm negative. Adoption fee is $175


Apply at Forgottenpaws.com. 
Approved applicant gets a two week trial prior to official adoption. Home visit is required. Masks will be worn.  

Located just north of Atlanta.

animal.description:
CARLOS is still looking for his FOSTER OR FOREVER home. 

He is such a sweet boy who loves toys and gets along great with all the dogs at the kennel house. He does need work when meeting new dogs on walks but sadly I haven’t had time to do what he needs. It’s a simple fix and he is so smart. 
Anyway...look at this handsome man!

He is 6 yrs old, 55 lbs but doesn’t look it in person. He is housebroken and crate trained but doesn’t need a crate. He loves toys and snuggling. He sleeps on a dog bed at night and prefers to be in your room. When he is sad he makes little tiny dog whiny noises that are so cute. 

Carlos is very healthy. From what we have found out, he originally was a stray taken in by Fulton county animal control. He had an injured eye that had to be removed and a gash on his leg.  That was 5 yrs ago. He was adopted and lived w a family for five years until they gave him away on craigslist. The next day, the people who got him brought him to me bc he was NOT GOOD W CATS.  I think this boy is very lucky that no one bad got him when he was given away! 

Neutered, fully vaccinated, heartworm negative, and microchipped. Adoption fee is $125.
 Approved applicants get a two week trial prior to official adoption.

Apply at Forgotten Paws.com. 

Located just north of Atlanta.

animal.description:
Howard desperately needs a foster or forever home. He has been here since 5/24/2013!!!!  No one has given him a chance

Crate trained, housebroken, walks well on leash: he just needs someone to love him.  He can be a silly boy full of love, hugs and kisses.

Howard has never had a normal home. He lived on a chain for the first year and a half of his life. He was able to run free at the kennel house for the first six months but then started having issues with a few of the other dominant male pitbull’s. Since then, Howard spends his evenings in a crate inside but goes out to his own yard to spend the day. He has playmates that go out to play with him but they have to have certain personalities. He loves goofy dogs and it doesn’t seem to matter if they’re male or female. Good with kids but a little exuberant for small ones. He has a very happy bouncy butt. No Cats 

Please consider opening your heart and home to this beautiful boy. He’s had a very bad life and has scars to show it. He deserves a good indoor, loving home and soft bed

No adoption fee. It has been sponsored by a supporter! 

Neutered, microchip, fully vaccinated, and heartworm negative. 
Apply at Forgottenpaws.com

animal.description:
LEROY IS STILL WAITING. It has been over a year since we rescued him from a neighbors shed and he still has no home.  She got him from an ex-boyfriend who couldn’t keep him anymore but he needs lots of playtime and exercise so instead of walking him to burn off his energy, she shoved him in the shed. Out of sight out of mind! 

Before this, Leroy lived in a home. He slept on the bed, cuddled on the couch, and was loved. He longs for that life again. 
3 yrs old, 60 lbs, pit mix.  

-pulls on leash but settles down after the  initial excitement wears off.  
-TALL FENCED YARD needed 
-loves to play fetch, sits, lays down, comes and gives kisses on command. 
Housebroken
crate trained
good with MOST other dogs.  He has had issues with larger dominant male dogs, and isn’t good w unneutered males. However, he has never had any issues at all with 99% of the dogs at the kennel house and never a female or small dog.  No cats. 
Leroy is good with older kids. He is good with them all but he still wants to jump when excited and although we have worked on this, he is still too much energy for small kids. 

Please consider FOSTERING OR ADOPTING THIS VERY SWEET HANDSOME BOY! 

Neutered, microchipped, fully vaccinated, heartworm negative.  Adoption fee is $150 so we can save the next one. 

Apply at Forgottenpaws.com

Approved homes get a two week trial prior to official adoption to make sure everyone is a good fit!

animal.description:
The best thing about Hank is that he loves to give me kisses and when he wants to play he comes and looks for me and starts crying. He is also so quiet that sometimes you even forget he is there.

His favorite food, mmmm. he eats and likes his dry dog food but once in a while he loves some pieces of chicken breast or ground beef mixed with it. He likes his mozzarella string cheese in the mornings and his chicken treats in the afternoon. He also enjoys his beef knee cap bones.

His favorite place to sleep I would say is his bed in the kitchen. We've tried several times to take him upstairs to the room but he is afraid and he comes down right away.

His quirkiest habit he has is to rub himself on the walls, bushes, and cars, lol. He also likes to crawl in the grass, he looks like a soldier at war.

His favorite toys are a stuffed chicken, porcupine, and a dog rope to pull.

He loves to go for a walk at night, that's his favorite part of the day.

animal.description:
Female - 7 years - 60 lbs - Microchipped - Spayed - TXHi! I'm Maybell. I am a 7-year-old, 60 lb spayed female. I am already housebroken and can be trusted home alone while loose in the house. While I will do well being crated overnight while my foster family is home, I do not like being crated while my family leaves the house. My foster family doesn't crate me at all anymore.
I am friendly with men and women after a few minutes to warm up to them. I cannot go to a home with children. I am more independent and enjoy sleeping off on my own, although I will occasionally seek out affection from my family. I am always happy to receive attention and petting from my family! I will welcome visitors into our home, although a lot of activity can make me anxious so a quieter home would be ideal.
I am friendly with other dogs and would do well with siblings or by myself. I love my toys and I still have a few favorites I am learning to share with my foster siblings! I am beginning to enjoy engaging play with my foster family! I cannot go to a home with cats.
I am a quiet, low energy girl, who has almost mastered my leash skills. I enjoy going out for my walks. I am prone to developing small benign masses which typically don't require medical intervention, although they may need to be removed if they grow in an uncomfortable location.
I am a happy, sweet girl who is ready to find that perfect forever family. Are you my perfect forever family?
Follow me on Facebook: #EchoDogMaybell
For more information, please contact adoptions@echodogs.org.

Echo Dogs fosters dogs in many states. Visit www.echodogs.org/available-dogs to see more of our dogs. Transportation for the adopted dog IS available. Remember, we are an all-volunteer foster rescue organization - we DO NOT have a physical shelter to visit. Our minimum adoption donation is $300. All dogs are spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations and micro-chipped. Puppies under 6 months old may not be spayed/neutered. This would be the responsibility of the adopter at their own expense. Proof of spay/neuter will be required!
To review our adoption procedure and submit an online application, visit: www.echodogs.org/procedure

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Clay County Animal Rescue & Shelter is located at 14400 Hwy. 45 in Louisville, IL. Our phone number is 618-665-3005. The shelter is open to the public 1-3 Monday-Saturday. Sundays we are open 1-4 to the public. If those times don't work, please call to set up a time to visit.

The typical adoption fee for dogs is $150. It includes vaccination, deworming , spay/neuter, heartworm testing on dogs of age and microchipping, which is now mandatory by state law. Some dogs we discount to as little as $50 due to sponsorship. Some dogs we ask a higher adoption fee, which helps us recoup expenses on heartworm treatment on other dogs.

All cats are spayed/neutered/vaccinated/flea treated/dewormed and microchipped prior to adoption. Cat adoption fees range from $60-$100. We spay/neuter/microchip/vaccinate and deworm all kittens and cats, prior to adoption. Our shyer/less adoptable cats are classed as "barn cats" and are free with a completed/approved barn cat application, which can be found on our website.

For updates on adoption events and more pics of pets available, go to our website, www.claycountyshelter.com or look for us on Facebook.

animal.description:
Well hello there!

My name is Ray Ray, which is short for Rachel Ray.  I'm named for her because I arrived at Lucies with buns in the oven.....get it, "buns in the oven"?  Hahahaha

Anyhoo, when I arrived I was heartworm positive.  Thank goodness I made it here because these peeps here are the best caretakers ever!!  I'm good and ready to go!

So, apparently I suffer from allergies.  We think it is a chicken allergy, although we are not certain.  I'm currently taking allergy medication and Benadryl.  They have considered getting me an allergy test, but I would have to be off all of my other medications first for several weeks, and that just leaves me completely miserable.

The gals here think I am absolutely the BEST dog!  I love everyone, humans, human kids and dogs.  I never meet a stranger.  I'm crate and leash trained.  Oh yeah, I LOVE water!!

Ironically, I could really benefit from a family that enjoys cooking (Rachel Ray) ;)  Through the process of elimination, they think I could overcome my allergies in a more pleasant way.

So what do you think?  I just know you would love me and I would love you too!  Inquire about me, you won't regret it!!

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
Male - 2 years - 80 lbs - Microchipped - Neutered - NYHi there! My name is Turbo and I am a 2-year-old, 80 lb neutered male. I am already housebroken and crate-trained. I am still young, so I will need to be crated when left home alone. My crate offers me a safe space when I get frightened.
I am very skittish with new people, although I will warm up to both men and women in my family. Young kids are too much for me, so please no small kids in my home. Older kids who are quieter and respectful of my space are ok with me. With my family at home, I am very affectionate and will seek affection. I am very Velcro to my foster dad! I am reactive to visitors to my home and will not be friendly. My foster family is working with a trainer to help me improve, but it will continue to be a work in progress in my forever home.
I do well with other dogs and enjoy playing with my foster sister! Due to my fear issues, I will require a confident canine sibling in my forever home to help guide me to knowing it is okay. I have been around cats and have been way too rough with them and would likely injure a cat, so I cannot go to a home with cats. I like playing with my toys, especially squeaky toys!
My foster parents have been working with me to learn how to sit, down, stay, place, and walk on a leash. I am still very scared about leaving my home, so I am only working on neighborhood walks first for now. I am intelligent, food motivated, and eager to please my family-so I should do well with continued training and socialization with my forever family! Could that be with you?
Follow me on Facebook: #EchoDogTurbo
For more information, please contact adoptions@echodogs.org.

Echo Dogs fosters dogs in many states. Visit www.echodogs.org/available-dogs to see more of our dogs. Transportation for the adopted dog IS available. Remember, we are an all-volunteer foster rescue organization - we DO NOT have a physical shelter to visit. Our minimum adoption donation is $300. All dogs are spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations and micro-chipped. Puppies under 6 months old may not be spayed/neutered. This would be the responsibility of the adopter at their own expense. Proof of spay/neuter will be required!
To review our adoption procedure and submit an online application, visit: www.echodogs.org/procedure

The NMDR Rehab Team is working with Dixie to help her work through some behavior challenges. She needs a family who will be extra patient with her, and who preferably has previous experience with dogs. To submit an application to adopt Dixie, visit https://nmdr.org/our-dogs/adopt/

Challenges for Dixie
Has a bite history
Fearful of new people and new situations
Needs a family who has another, more confident dog of a similar size, experience with fearful dogs and no children
Needs yard enclosed by a 4' minimum solid fence
Her guardian will need to be very patient and let Dixie make progress at her own speed
Needs to be adopted locally (CO front range)

Fun facts about Dixie
Has become much braver since she first arrived at NMDR
Pretty good at walking on leash
Likes other dogs but doesn't play much
Likes fresh air, sunshine and cheese

animal.description:
Jolly is a 1 year old male German Shepherd mix. He weighs 73 lbs. We will consider adopters for Jolly only if they have Shepherd or similar breed experience. He is doing great working on obedience and leash skills at our adoption center. Jolly is a friendly boy but has lacked structure in his early development so he needs a firm and fair leader to bring him to his full potential. 

Jolly is happy to meet everyone and has an overall happy personality .He acts like a big puppy and is learning to be more aware of his body and size. Jolly is mouthy with treats but takes correction well and is being much more gentle with work on this. For this reason and his size, we recommend mature 
children in his household. 13+ year old kids, dog savvy kids 

He is strong on the leash but has been working well in a Halti during training. Jolly is comfortable being petted all over. He is high energy and needs a lot of exercise - active adopters needed. Jolly can be "too much" for many dogs so it would need to be the right match. He was loose and comfortable in our large fenced area at our FL rescue and was not a problem with other dogs.

Not cat tested. Positive toy drive and lots of food drive. Wants to please and learn.

Want to Adopt? 1) Fill out an application on theluckypuppy.org The donation fees are minimum $475 for puppies up to 6 months, minimum $400 for dogs 7 months to 6 years and minimum $ 300 for 7+ years/Special Needs. 2) Once your application is in, our adoption coordinator will contact you and complete a vet check and home visit (possibly electronic). 3) Once approved, please schedule a meet and greet to see the dogs. Meet and greets are by appointment only for approved adopters.

Jolly is available in NY through the Go North Program of The Lucky Puppy Rescue centered in Bonifay and Panama City, FL (NY Lic #1054). The minimum donation $400 adoption fee includes transportation from FL to NY, spay/neuter surgery, vaccinations, de-worm, flea prevention, heartworm prevention and martingale safety collar. Adoption fee payment methods accepted are credit, debit, Paypal and bank checks. No personal checks or cash. Applications must be submitted through our website - theluckypuppy.org - thank you! You may copy and paste the following link to apply: http://www.theluckypuppy.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Luna is a gentle hearted 6 to 8 year old Giant Schnauzer. She is a bundle of energy, is housetrained, leash trained and knows all of her basic commands including come, sit, stay, wait, and go to your bed. She really likes to go far car rides and is comfortable travelling. She loves the attention of her family so much that she has some separation anxiety and does not like to be alone for long. She loves to be outside, especially in cooler weather and benefits from long walks and lots of play time. She plays well with other dogs close to her size, but seems to regard small dogs as toys and is not able to treat them gently which can result in them being injured.

While Luna is not aggressive with the people in her household, she can be timid of strangers who come into her territory and has barks and sometimes lunges at them. She is always introduced to new people carefully. Despite this, when taken to the groomers or the vet, Luna has always acted friendly and in an appropriate manner, comfortable to be treated or groomed without complaint. She also generally reacts well to people she meets on walks.

Luna has a pronounced startle response that can be unpredictable. Because of this and her inexperience with small children, Luna would probably be best in a home with no children or older teens. She has a cyst on her back near her hindquarters that has been biopsied and is benign. It has not grown in sized in a couple of years and is considered no danger to her, but is quite noticeable when she has her short summer hair cut. She is also prone to raised hair follicles that go away on their own. They do not bother her and only need to be watched to make sure they don't get infected. She takes Stilbestrol every five days for minor bladder leakage often seen in spayed dogs. She has shown no side effects.

She has been living in a rural home and property and enjoys the space; she would not do well as a city dog. Luna is not a good choice for first time dog owners; she requires a house with securely fenced yard and in the suburbs or in the country. Her family is sorry that they have to re-home her but she is too rough with the small dogs who are getting older and they are nervous she may hurt one of them.

animal.description:
Meet Brindle beauty Roxie! This 43 pound, 1-year- old girl has been a charmer in her foster home. She has a very sweet nature (even the trainers she’s worked with have said so!)—she’s affectionate with her people and loves to snuggle. She’s excellent indoors—she’s house trained, happy hanging out in her crate and playing with her toys, doesn't chew stuff, and isn’t barky. She’s very content sleeping in her crate at night, and she’s working on spending time there when her humans are out of the house too. She has been working with her foster parents on walking nicely and has made huge progress. She’ll now walk at your side and while she can be reactive to some dogs, she’s getting better at minding her own business. 
Roxie is very food-motivated and takes well to positive reinforcement and treats.  She’s great at learning commands and responds well to verbal and visual cues, and will thrive with an owner who will keep working on her obedience training. Roxie would probably do best as the only dog in the home, and would love to either have a backyard she can run around in, or an active owner who enjoys jogging or other outdoor activity. Roxie will thrive in a home as the only dog with an experienced handler and no young children. 

www.rescuecity.nyc/adopt. 

We are currently facilitating safe adoptions with COVID-19 protocols and adopt out to NYC and surrounding states only - NY CT PA & NJ. 

**If a dog is listed on petfinder as available then we are still accepting applications for that dog. We urge you to apply as soon as possible to be considered to adopt the dog you’re interested **

Thank you for wanting to give one of our adoptables a loving home! Please follow us on Instagram at @rescuecity for more adoptable updates!

animal.description: Jo Jo is an approximately 1 year old male neutered pit bull who presented to us very ill at the beginning of December 2020. He was diagnosed with leptospirosis which is a bacterial infection that can attack the liver and kidneys. In Jo Jo's case, he has recovered from the infection great; however, he was left with very mild residual elevations in his kidney values. He is not showing any signs of kidney disease; however, it is important to note that this infection did compromise his kidneys, therefore he may be more prone to kidney disease in his future. We do have him on a kidney diet just as a precaution. Other dogs and children are unknown and will require a supervised visit with staff. If placed with cats; we ask for a slow, well-managed introduction.

animal.description:
Foxy is a year and a half years old mixed breed dog.  She came to us heartworm positive and pregnant, had babies here and now she's had heartworm treatment and is ready for her forever home.  She is a very sweet girl but is high energy.  She is only about 35 pounds. She loves to run so a fenced in yard is a MUST! She also does not like cats so needs a home with NO cats.  She loves other dogs.

Adopters must live within a 100-mile radius of Joliet, IL to be considered. The adoption fee is $425. This covers all shots, spay/neutering and microchip.

To be considered for this dog. Please fill out an application here: https://www.pawsup4rescue.org/dog-cat-applicaiton

Our adoption process typically takes from one to two weeks. When you find an animal you are interested in, we ask that you fill out an application as a first step so we can determine if your family is a good fit for the animal. If you are, then we will contact you to arrange a time for you and your family to meet the animal so you can decide if it is a good fit. If you currently have dogs, we require that the dogs be present at the meeting to make sure it's a good fit all around. Once compatibility is determined, we move on to the paperwork and finalizing the adoption. 

If the meet is not a good fit, we will keep your application on file for up to 1 year and we will gladly consider your family for another dog. 

Follow us on FACEBOOK: www.Facebook.com/PawsUp4Rescue/

animal.description: Calling all *experienced* beagle lovers! Lincoln is a 4.5 year old beagle who was surrendered to our shelter due to his aggression around human food.  They also mentioned that he is easily startled when sleeping and can be reactive.  These issues were never properly addressed when he was a puppy.  It has gotten to the point where this issue will need to be carefully managed in his new home.  Lincoln loves his human friends and really enjoys meeting new people and receiving affection.  Lincoln can be dog-selective and his previous owner said that he was scared of overly excited dogs.  He is a happy go lucky guy but he definitely does have his quirks! Lincoln does fine around dog food and treats, so we believe that his issue lies strictly with high valued human food.  He will need to be kept away when people are eating and will need strict boundaries implemented to help with his lack of impulse control.  He is already crate trained, so this could be a good tool to use.  Lincoln loves to be outside with his favorite volunteers and enjoys his daily walks! He would be a great working dog and would be happy to be your adventure buddy out in the woods.  He will need an adult-only home with no children that visit.  If you have any questions about him, please send an email and we can discuss his behavior further.

animal.description:
NOTE: THIS IS A COURTESY POSTING ONLY!
THIS PET IS NOT AVAILABLE THROUGH BROTHER WOLF ANIMAL RESCUE. 
PLEASE CONTACT THE OWNER FOR MORE INFORMATION OR TO MAKE AN APPLICATION FOR ADOPTION. 

The owner's email is: leahmw5@gmail.com

Keva is a wonderful girl. My family took her in at the beginning of the pandemic as her 1st home was not working out. Due to where Keva was born, she doesn't do well with children and her 1st home needed to find her a new environment quickly. Keva does not have a problem when on leash and passing children, she just does better in a home without small humans running around. Keva is shy and was initially fearful of us, but warmed up within the week and now she is one of the most loyal and lovely companions. She is about 1.5-2 years old, so she has some puppy spring in her still - we get her exercise by playing fetch a lot and she LOVES it. Keva's favorite things include car rides, playing with other energetic dogs, HIKING, and chewing on toys at home. Our need to re-home her is due to our dog of 6 years who we have found does not do well with Keva (not Keva's fault). Additionally, Keva is fearful of strangers at first (she prefers to hang out in her crate when people come over) and we feel a home with less foot traffic and traveling would be better for her. Please reach out to me to learn more about Keva and to discuss if you may be the right fit - We want her next home to be her forever place. Extra thoughts: Keva needs a crate - We call this her "house" and she goes there to have a safe space when she's overwhelmed - Keva has some "confinement" anxiety. This meaning that she does best when left to roam in the *dog proofed* house when people aren't home - Keva needs a home that can give her plenty of consistent exercise. Keva has not lived with cats and we assume she may do better in a home without cats.

animal.description:
Howdy,

My name is Lefty and I'm the rootinist, tootinist pup this side of the Rio Grande!!  Before you ask, yes I do have a pal named Pancho.  ;)  Here's our story.

So, here I was presumably dumped in the middle of Nowhere, Texas, when a nice gentleman saw me and picked me up.  He was driving along wondering where he could find a place to keep me, as he didn't have any available space.

A few miles down the road appeared another dumped puppy, who was of no relation to me.  What are the odds?  2 dumped puppies and one nice, caring man to pick us up and save us.  He took us in and cleaned us up and fed us, but it was really putting him in a bind.

He called those wonderful people at Lucies and they agreed to take us.  They really are cool people, if I do say so myself!  

Now. I am all vetted and healthy.  I'm ready for a furever family.  One that won't mistreat me and dump me.  One that will give me the affection and I that I crave.  I'm so hoping it's you.

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
Meet Rosie Sue! Are you looking for a new BFF that is fully house trained and loves to cuddle....Rosie is ready!

She is about 3 years old, Crate trained and good with kids!


ADOPTION PROCESS
1. Review our adoption contract and application.

2. Call your vet and references to inform them that a rescue representative will be calling.

3. Complete adoption application and submit at  https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/HRMD/Dog

4. You will be notified of outcome of your application within 3-5 days.

5. If approved, you will be introduced to the foster to schedule a meeting within 5 days. Guidelines for the meeting are:

- Bring a leash and collar and be prepared to take the animal home directly from the meeting.

- Meeting should be no longer than 1 hour. Our fosters are volunteers and we value and respect their time and personal commitments. 

- All members of the household (including other dogs) must be present.

- Please be prepared to submit adoption fee via PayPal at the meeting – We do not accept payments prior to the meeting. 

- If all goes well, the dog will go home with you directly after the meeting. If you are not ready to adopt at the conclusion of the meeting, please understand that we may process other applications for the dog. Because we have a limited amount of foster homes, we cannot hold dogs past adoption. 

6. Please review these resources prior to the meeting to be prepared with what to expect when bringing a new dog home: 

a. ttps://www.petfinder.com/dogs/bringing-a-dog-home/tips-for-first-30-days-dog/

b. https://www.dogstardaily.com/free-downloads

7. Love on your new family member and join our Alumni Group! We love seeing updates on the happy endings to your story.

animal.description:
Hola!

My name is Pancho.  Not like the restaurant, and definitely not like the general of the Mexican Revolutionary War!  I'm a lover not a fighter after all.  It's actually a nickname for Francisco.  Cool huh?  Oh and yes, I do have a pal named Lefty ;)  Here's our story.

So, here I was presumably dumped in the middle of Nowhere, Texas, when a nice gentleman saw me and picked me up.  He was driving along wondering where he could find a place to keep me, as he didn't have any available space.

A few miles down the road appeared another dumped puppy, who was of no relation to me.  What are the odds?  2 dumped puppies and one nice, caring man to pick us up and save us.  He took us in and cleaned us up and fed us, but it was really putting him in a bind.

He called those wonderful people at Lucies and they agreed to take us.  They really are cool people, if I do say so myself!  They call me their little timber wolf.  Howwwwllll!!!  ;)

Now. I am all vetted and healthy.  I'm ready for a furever family.  One that won't mistreat me and dump me.  One that will give me the affection and I that I crave.  I'm so hoping it's you.

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description: Ellie is a 3 year old pocket pittie looking for a new family! She came into the shelter as a stray and was extremely underweight.  She does look like a puppy- most likely due to malnutrition, her growth was stunted.  Even though humans let her down in the past, she holds no grudges.  Ellie loves everyone that she meets and can’t get enough love.  She will jump right into your lap craving more attention because simply petting her is not enough! Ellie can be reactive with dogs an it seems she is more likely to befriend a male dog than a female dog.  This youngster is super energetic and would benefit from an active family to keep her mind and body busy.  Ellie weighs only 42lbs and could possibly make a good apartment dog, as long as she gets the proper amount of outdoor exercise time! Older teens or adult-only home preferred, since she can sometimes be a little intense with her food.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Nona was surrendered by her owner when she could no longer take care of her. She was rescued at 3 months old, and was incorrectly diagnosed once she was taken to get a 2nd opinion, the Dr said her blindness was due to a swollen nerve in her ear, she was put on treatment and in no time she could see again! Nona is an incredible dog, very friendly, and falls in love with everyone she meets whether it's people or other dogs. She has wonderful social skills, walks well on a leash, crate trained, rides well in the car, loves squeaky toys, and loves to play with her foster siblings. Nona still has a lot to learn, she's is an active girl who will love to go on adventures and explore new things. She's very loving and obedient. A loving family willing to continuing giving her her daily supplement so she can continue enjoying her life to the fullest will be the perfect match for this wonderful sweet girl. In new environments and when stressed or excited, Nona will still turn in circles as she did prior to being rescued, but she settles once comfortable in a familiar place with a stable routine.

animal.description:
Hi there!

My name is Pocket.  How are you? Good?  I'm good as well, thanks for asking.  I didn't start off so well though.  Let me tell me my story.

An elderly gentleman had gone out to his backyard to feed his 2 dogs.  Well, poof there I was.  He had no idea how I got there, and honestly neither do I!  I stayed there with the other 2 dogs, who I made friends with.  The dogs were cool, but the old man, not so much.  Not sure why I felt that way about him.  After all, he was feeding and taking care of me now as well.

I was just really scared of him.  So he called Lucies and of course, they found room for me!  They took me in and are taking really good care of me.  While I like it here, I would really like to have a family for my very own.  One that I don't have to share with anyone else.

I'm a shy and timid dog, but am slowly coming out of my turtle shell. (See what I did there?)  ;)  I'm crate trained and am learning to train on a leash, however I have not completely mastered that skill yet. 

I get along well with other dogs and like to romp and play.  I do tend to carry myself like a tiny show dog, prancing around here and there.  I'd love to show you sometime.  I'm sure you'll be impressed!!

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
Rhythm-Australian Cattle Dog/mixed breed-male-neutered-1 year-Adoption fee: $275 plus tax. Update: Rhythm's fee has been partially sponsored by Jack. His fee is reduced to $90 plus tax.  Meet Rhythm!  Isn't he gorgeous!?!  Rhythm is a sweet guy that needs a new home. He is smart and willing to learn.  Rhythm just wants to be by your side and seems like a really loyal dog.  He seems like a really good buddy dog.  He most likely would like a home where he can do things with his owner, go on car rides and just be a best buddy.  Rhythm LOVES treats.  So much so he can forget there are human fingers involved.  He will snatch them as fast as he can. He needs some work on this.    We are looking for a home without young kids. Please do your research on Australian Cattle Dogs before considering adoption. This breed has unique needs and personalities.  They are active, need a lot of exercise and are really smart.  They are bred to perform demanding tasks and take their jobs seriously. They are often surrendered due to owners not understanding this when they get a Cattle Dog.   Rhythm needs a new owner that knows that they are getting into! Unique thing about Rhythm is he has a docked tail.   

I am fixed, current on my rabies, distemper and kennel cough vaccinations. I am heartworm negative(dogs 6 months and older are tested at CCHS) and started on heartworm prevention. I have been de-wormed and I have also been microchipped. I will also be inspected by 
 a vet and receive a Certificate of Veterinary Inspection.  If you are interested in me, please head to the CCHS website at www.cchswi.org and fill out an application. Thank you! DATCP License 266742-DS

Count on a big fast hug and kiss when you meet sweet Clarice! This friendly, steady wagging bully mix is so gentle and well balanced and a true friend to all. A mid-sized girl at 42lbs, take one look at her and you just know she has not led a pampered life but she's such a great sport and takes everything in great stride, so she likely does not know how life should be for a pretty girl such as herself. Her days of having multiple litters are now over and her mommy apron strings now retired. Clarice enjoyed trotting around our play area all the while coming over to check on me to deliver a fast smooch, a quick little hug or a fun little hula dance. Clarice is friendly and snuggly and seemed most content while simply sitting with me on the cold cement bench in the play yard. She checked out the cars as they came and went and made sure I had plenty of wet nose nudges. Great choice as a family pet but she does require a home without cats. You know you want to meet this great girl, so book a time to come on out. She'll not disappoint you.

Our adoption fee includes neutering, microchip, appropriate shots, and a post adoption veterinarian wellness check.

I am a very high energy dog. It appears that I have a bit of the herding breed in my lines. I would love a family that already has experience with herding dog breeds. I am also deaf and need a family who will be patient and help me learn sign commands. If you have experience with deaf dogs or dogs that have had some loss of hearing that would be a bonus. One more thing, because I wasn't properly cared for the first go around, I have heartworm disease.no worries, it can be treated. The wonderful folks at Hertferd County Animal Shelter where I originally came from, have donated $200 towards my treatment. After my treatment and rest, I will need an active lifestyle. Any children in the home should be 12 years and up and no apartments please! If you are looking to rescue and love and Underdog and you are ready to change a life, ask for me Tonka. A manager would be happy to answer any questions and counsel you on my unique adoption. See you soon!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Ruth (rpriestley@sciotodowns.com) for more information about this pet.Linnette's adoption donation is $400 and she is being fostered in Central Ohio. She has been spayed, microchipped, received her rabies, distemper/parvo, bivalent canine influenza, and bordetella vaccines, tested negative for heartworms and started on flea prevention, as well as flea prevention. She has also had a dental cleaning.
She will require a home with a secure, physically fenced yard and a companion dog of similar size.

Linnette, or Lynn, came into rescue from a commercial breeder and she is making a lot of progress in rescue. Lynn is an approximately 4-5 year old Papillon who is very sweet and learning to be a dog. Like most mill dogs, she is more comfortable being around other dogs but is quickly learning to be the social butterfly. Linnette does well with housetraining if kept on a schedule and continues to improve her leash skills. She will require a home with a secure, physically fenced yard and a companion dog of similar size. PLEASE NOTE: If you are viewing this biography on a website other than the Ohio Fuzzy Pawz website, not all information transfers to partner websites in some instances. If you go to the individual webpage of our dogs, you will be able to get more information each dog.

Visual breed identification in dogs can be unreliable so, in many cases, we are only guessing at the predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

Our Adoption Process

The adoption process has several steps involved.

Please review prior to submitting an application.
Our adoption process is detailed here:

http://www.ohiofuzzypawz.com/info/adoption

Our volunteers work very diligently to process each application and we try to ensure that we are making the best match possible for each dog. We do not schedule meetings with dogs until an application has been approved. It can take up to a few weeks to process an application or as little time as a few days, from the time you submit an application, please be prepared to adopt as we cannot hold dogs.

Special Requirements

Some dogs may have special requirements (for example, medications, a fence) -- if you apply for a dog, please be sure to read over the biography completely to see if there are any special needs and if you're home would be suitable. If we indicate on the dog's biography that a fence is required, this means your home must have a physical fence. Other dogs may require a "strong vet reference" which indicates that we are looking for a home that has a documented history of veterinary care with previous pets.

The first step in our process is to submit an online adoption application at www.ohiofuzzypawz.com/forms. The application MUST include the personal references and veterinary, grooming, and landlord references (if applicable) and their respective contact information. If you do not include the references and the contact information, your application will be delayed as it CANNOT be processed. Once the references have been successfully completed, a home visit is then scheduled when a rescue representative can meet all members of the family or residents of the home.
No application is approved prior to the home visit being done.
At that point, the Directors will discuss any and all applications on a foster dog and make a selection--in many cases, there are multiple applications for each dog, so please be understanding that our only priority is the successful placement of each of our foster dogs.

Out of State Adoptions

We do adopt out of state to outstanding applicants, however, our process requires a home visit, so out of state adoptions can take longer.
We do not ship our dogs, adopters should be prepared to pick up the dog in Central Ohio.

Meet Pebbles. She is a 6-year old, 58 pound pibble in an adorable compact ("low-rider") frame with cartoonish features to match her name. It's hard not to fall in love with her at first sight given how cute she is, with her floppy Dumbo ears, soulful eyes, and a little "blep" tongue that comes out when she's excited. She is an affectionate girl who loves people, often leaning in and flopping down for a belly rub. Pebbles is the perfect mix of dog: calm inside the house and active outside. She loves long walks, but is as happy cuddling on the couch (super polite - waits to be asked up). She is fully crate and house trained and already knows a few commands (sit, down, and always will rollover). While in foster, she has been working on her leash skills and has made great progress, though will need her future family to continue this training. She is a gentle girl so could make a great family dog. Pebbles is dog selective (no experience with cats), so looking to be the only pet or potentially with dogs her size. Whoever adopts her will have a best friend for life!

The adoption fee for this dog is $425

animal.description:
Meet Reyna! 

This gorgeous girl is sweet as can be. She is a precious 55 lbs girl, about 2 years old. Her ears were chopped off by whoever previously had her, so she has a tough look, but is such a sweet girl. She has tons of personality, and is a happy go lucky girl who loves to play with toys. She LOVES bouncy balls.

Reyna is a great car rider and companion! She would love to ride along. She will look at you with the most loving eyes and with gratitude. She makes for a really good best friend. She is little bit clingy so she would love someone who has availability for her. She would love to snuggle if you will let her. 

 She should be an only dog in the house, but She has no issue passing other dogs on walks or trotting happily by them at boarding (check out her video!). She may do okay with a super chill, laid back sibling who can help her rebuild her confidence, but would probably do best as a single dog for right now. She thinks kitties are for chasing, too, so none of those please! 
 

Reyna needs someone willing to work with her a bit. She crates up fine but does have some normal bad habits such as jumping up when she is excited. So basic training would be good. She needs someone experienced to draw boundaries and redirect. 

Reyna is medium energy, and always up to play or go on adventures! She loves going for car rides, and has never met a human that she doesn't like. She's a favorite at the vet's office, pet store, and boarding kennel, and it's not hard to see why! This happy girl will light up your life, and give you so much love in return for being her forever human.

Reyna is potty trained and crate trained. 

Reyna has energy to go on hikes and adventures. But knows when to calm down and just show love. 

Reyna is up to date on all vaccines, spayed, microchipped, wormed, and comes with 6 months of heartworm prevention and a month of free pet insurance through Trupanion. The vet says she looks to be in great condition!

Please fill out an application:

https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/19754/generic

Coordinator: Olga@threelittlepittiesrescue.org

animal.description:
IMPORTANT!!!   All adoptions are by appointment only going forward and are spaced 30 minutes apart. PLEASE call the shelter directly during business hours for more information (see number below).  You need to make sure that the animal in which you have an interest is still available and to set up an appointment to meet the specific animal.  Once you arrive at the shelter for your scheduled appointment, please follow the directions that you were given over the telephone. If you are running late for your appointment or will be unable to make your scheduled appointment time, notify staff immediately. This will enable them to schedule that time for another prospective adoptive family. If necessary, they will be able to reschedule your appointment to a more convenient time.  

NO CHILDREN!!! Needs to be the only dog in the family.
FRECKLES is a brown and white mixture of cattle dog and boxer. She is estimated to be a year old and has been at the shelter about a month at the time of this posting. She has been settling in to the routine and being evaluated for adoptability. FRECKLES was scared upon arrival and has gone back-and-forth between liking other dogs and not liking them so much. Staff does not actually train the dogs at the shelter, but does give them time to relax and show their true nature to the extent possible given that they are kept in kennels and usually housed alone until space restraints require them to attempt to pair suitable animals to accommodate overloads. Based on their overall evaluation of FRECKLES, staff now indicates that while she is adoptable and could do well in a farm setting, she is not appropriate for adoption to a home with children and needs to be the only dog in the family if she is to be a pet. She definitely needs to be confined to a properly fenced and secure yard or kept inside the home at all times except for when you personally take her out to do her business. She is a dominant dog and needs someone who is willing to work with a qualified trainer, or who has the professional skill set themselves, to make sure she remains a good dog in our community.

Adoption fees are $80 for dogs.  Cat adoption fees are $50. Cash or check only. Please be sure to take the exact amount with you.


NOTE: All shelter fees are under review and may be changed or modified at any time without advance notice.

The shelter routinely vaccinates all healthy appearing animals upon their arrival at the shelter and deworms them.  Any animals not already spayed/neutered must have the procedure done through the veterinary clinic that contracts with the county before that animal can be released from the clinic to the new family. By state law, animals old enough to be given a rabies vaccine, must have that vaccine done, as well.  The vaccine is given by the veterinary clinic staff at a separate cost to the adoptive family. 

Hold periods for every incoming animal vary for several reasons including, but not limited to, whether the animal came in from the Cumberland County area, or from the City of Crossville, which contracts with the county for its animal shelter services.  Check with the staff to verify the availability date of every animal for which you have an interest.

For more information on this pet, call the shelter at (931)484-8525. The shelter is open Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday from 10am to 2pm. Closed Wednesday and Sunday and county observed holidays.

animal.description:
*Please read the full bio*
If you are interested in meeting me , we require an approved application. If you have questions regarding adoption, please visit our website --> www.adoptionfirstanimalrescueky.com
Please do not email us asking if the dog is available. We will not respond to emails that can be answered on our website.
Valentine here, I am finally looking for a forever home make sure to read all of my bio & check out my pictures.
I came from Mexico, I was found hurt and needed surgery on my jaw, missing a leg, and both eyes.. I then went to an amazing lady in Texas where my rescue saved me. They don't know much about me except I'm roughly under a year old, 24 pounds, and a total ham. I have no eyes and only have three legs, they aren't sure what happened but it doesn't stop me one bit. I love to run around with my friends they are so much fun. I can't see them but I can hear every sound they make and I can keep up with them - Im pretty fast I say. When I go outside I get so excited I jump around like a kangaroo and my foster mom laughs. I love to snuggle with my foster mom, I cuddle real good. She tells me one day I'll get a new mommy and she will love me just like she does even though I look alittle different.
I promise to give you all the love, if you chose me.
Complete Application

You must complete the adoption application in full to be considered for adoption.

Home Check
All adoptions do require a home check. If you are not comfortable with a home check please do not apply. We want to ensure the safety of our dogs and to make sure the adoptive family is comfortable.
Meet and Greet
If your application has been approved we will schedule a meet and greet for the dog of your choice or for a few we think might be a good fit for your family.
Sign Adoption Contract
This must be read and signed prior to adoption.
Adoption Fee
Once everything has been reviewed the adoption fee will need to be paid. Puppies under 6 months is $300, over 6 months is $250, over 10 years is $150. Adoption fee includes: -Spay or Neuter -Microchip (additional registration fee required to transfer ownership to adopters) -Up to date on vaccinations -All animals have been examined by a veterinarian ** All adoption fees are non refundable

Katrina is a tan lab mix female dog.  She is about 2 years old, weighs 40 pounds and is heart worm negative. Her adoption fee will include vaccinations, worming, microchipping and spaying.  Katrina is easy-going and loves affection.  She is fair on a leash and needs some practice.  Katrina loves treats and will be easy to train. We think Katrina is good with cats...at least she did well with the shelter cat....she never tried to run after the cat and seemed interested in getting to know the cat.  I am betting she will be good with kids and other dogs because of her sweet personality.  Come meet Katrina and see for yourself if she might be a great fit for you and your family.

1/20/2021 - My name is Rex!

Rex: ESTIMATED DOB: 1/19/ 2016 Beagle/cattle dog mix, male, house trained, good on leash, NO DOGS,  not good in crate
 
Rex is a lovable teddy bear who is now ready to find his perfect match. He loves exchanging affection and giving kisses. He is a giant lap dog that prefers cuddles to playtime. He has experience with older children. Rex is house trained and uses a doggie door. He walks well on the leash for leisurely strolls. Rex is looking for an experienced adopter due to the fact he is dog selective and does not always back down if confronted by another dog.

animal.description:
Ellie’s family realized that their new baby was highly allergic, and they turned to us to help her find a new home. She loves to go for walks with friends, both furry and human. She takes treats gently like a good girl, plays well with other dogs, enjoys the company of cats (she lived with cats before), and has more energy than most girls her age (9-years-old)!

Ellie is fairly food-motivated, which is always a plus when training or when trying to get her to cooperate (though this isn’t a dog that protests too much in the first place). She enjoys play time but walking and getting pets are her favorite activities.

We think Ellie would be a great addition to any family, and we think you should come meet her and find out for yourself just how great she is.

If you are interested in meeting any of our adoptable dogs, please fill out an application. To apply, please visit our web site: https://www.mlar.org/adoption-overview 

E-mails regarding adoption are not considered an application. 

Out-of-state applicants (outside of PA/NJ/DE) will not be considered, unless there are special circumstances. Please visit our web site for more detailed information on the animals in our care, our educational campaigns, and for helpful tips on adoption. www.MLAR.org

animal.description:
Bart is a special needs senior looking for a very special home. When Bart came to FARM it didn’t take long for us to figure out just how special he is. Bart is both blind and deaf. He also has what’s known as short snout syndrome which means he breaths very loud. At 11 years old Bart’s favorite activity is napping and eating. This boy LOVES to eat. His home requirements include no steps or the ability to block steps off so he doesn’t fall and a nice soft bed that will stay in the same spot forever so he always knows where it is. He will take about 2 weeks to to settle into a new home and learn his new environment. He might not be able to see or hear but he can smell and always knows when it’s dinner time. Also, his voice works and he isn’t shy about using it when he wants something. If you are looking for a senior snuggly, snorty pug Bart is your guy. 

If you are interested in Bart, or any other FARM dog, please submit an application for review by our Adoption Committee. Meet and greets for approved adopters will be by appointment only. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out a dog application which can be found at http://fallstonanimalrescue.org/adopt/ and e-mail it to fallstonrescue@aol.com

It can take up to 2 weeks to process an application; we suggest following up by email on the status if you have not received a reply within 3-5 days. We are an all-volunteer based rescue and we ask for your patience if we are slow to respond.

Please understand that we fit the dog with the home we feel is best suited and will accept multiple applications for one dog. We have strict requirements for families with children under 10 since many of our dogs are grumpy and may not do well with children. Some dogs will have fence requirements, while others may not. It is preferred you are within a 2 hour drive from our Rescue Center in Fallston, MD and preference will be given to local applicants.

A pet is a lifetime commitment and it is our duty to do our very best to place them correctly the first time around. We do not take the adoption process lightly. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
"Every dog has its day." Meet dapper-looking Cadman, a mild manner Pyr born around June 2017. Cadman, weighing 75 lbs, was rescued by the Great Pyrenees Rescue Society from a Texas animal shelter as an owner surrender.

Cadman is reserved when first meeting new people and dogs. He prefers to go slow in new situations. He would thrive in an active home with older, considerate kids and a resident canine companion to show him the ropes. He is okay around cats.

He is a loving, intelligent Pyr and needs confident leaders in his family familiar with Pyr characteristics and habits. Please complete an Adoption Application if Cadman would fit perfectly with your family today and every day.

All dogs and puppies require VISIBLE fencing

Adoption Fee: $300. (Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm test, rabies, distemper, parvo and health certificate for travel). Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($225). Adoption applications can be found on our website at https://www.greatpyreneesrescuesociety.org/.

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer!

animal.description:
Teagan is a 2.5 year old beauty who would love to be off and running in your large, securely-fenced yard. She is a “pocket Setter” who weighs about 30 pounds, so she is lap-sized as well. What could be better than a Setter who loves to run and loves to cuddle.

True to her breed, Teagan loves to run hard chasing birds and squirrels, which means she needs a Setter-interesting yard with at least a 6-foot fence. She is the poster girl for the saying “A tired Setter is a happy Setter.” Teagan needs a very active person. A good size yard is not enough. This girl needs someone that will ideally run, or at least take her on long/fast daily walks.  She gets along well with other dogs and likes playing with toys, but if Teagan could make a list the #1 entry would be “Running after birds and squirrels.” Happily, #2 would be “Cuddling with humans.”

Teagan walks well on a leash and is house trained. She has good recall in the yard, but could never be trusted off-leash in an unfenced area. Her foster mom says, “She is really fast!!” She has lived peacefully with the resident cat, but would need supervision and slow acclimation in a home with cats to make sure she would be safe with a new cat. Because of Teagan’s prey-drive, outdoor cats are not an option. Teagan needs a home with Setter or Setter like experience. She needs a home with furniture privileges. Teagan has not been in a home with children, and she is very active, so she is only a candidate for homes with children 7+ years of age.

Teagan is fully-vetted and microchipped. She is currently in a foster home in Houston, TX.

For an application to adopt or for more information about Southwest English Setter Rescue including our adoption requirements and transport availability, please go to http://www.swesr.org/. Please call us at 214-997-3885 if you have any questions.

animal.description:
Sasha
Rottweiller/Lab Mix
Gender: Female
DOB: 05/12/2020
Adoption Fee: $200.00
Hi there! I'm Sasha! I'm a very sweet, loving dog that really craves your attention! I get along with my friend Guac here at HSMC very well, we play together like we are siblings! I love to play with toys and other dogs. I can climb short fences so I should not be left outside alone. I am good with children and people of all ages. If you want to make me a part of your furever family, come see me today!Please read the animal bios completely before requesting additional information as we do our best to answer the most frequently ask questions in these bios. 

In order to adopt one of our animals an application must be submitted and approved. You can find these applications by going to http://humanemorgan.org/index.php?page=adoption 

ABOUT ADOPTING FROM THE HSMC: 
The shelter address is 1170 Fairground Rd. Madison, GA 30650. For more information on any of our pets, please feel free to email us at INFO@HUMANEMORGAN.ORG give us a call at 706-343-9977. 
All dogs are heartworm negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
All cats are FeLv/FIV negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
We are open 10am-5pm Monday-Saturday, we schedule our last adoption at 4pm everyday to allow our staff enough time to feed and walk dogs. 
We are an animal shelter and therefore are not able to individually potty train our residents. Many adult dogs do arrive ""house broken"" however due to animal behavior any change in environment will make an emotional impact on the animals and therefore initiate unwanted behaviors during the acclamation period. Please keep this in mind. Puppies do not have the biological maturity to maintain absolute bladder or bowel control and will require a certain degree of potty training and house breaking. Please consider the time and commitment it takes to provide the necessary building blocks for these special babies, prior to submitting your application. 
If you have any questions please email us at info@humanemorgan.org and provide name of the animal you are interested in, in the subject line. 
Thank you, HSMC Staff 

ADOPTION FEES Adoption Fees may change without notice. Always verify the fee when finalizing the adoption. 
~ Cats and Kittens ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $100 
* 1-5 Years = $75 
* Over 5 Years = $50 
** Purebred cats and kittens may be subject to special pricing 

~ Mix Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $200 
* 1 -3 Years = $175 
* 4-8 Years = $150 
* Over 8 Years = $100

~ Purebred and Designer Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $375 
* 1-3 Years = $350 
* 4-8 Years = $275 
* Over 8 Years = $150 

~ Medical and Special Needs ~ 
We have rescued dogs and cats which require additional medical care or that have special needs which are not life threatening. In these cases we may require a higher fee to help recoup the costs of their care while at our rescue.

animal.description:
Hi!! My rescue name is Jeff, but my foster mom calls me Boomer. I'm a 3-ish yo male staffie mix and I am a total goofball! My foster mom has a giggle ball that I obsess over and will entertain myself with for hours if she let me! I also love to play with one of my foster brothers and try to get my older foster sisters to play, but they don't want to. I usually prefer submissive dogs since I like to be the boss of the group; I especially like the girls! 

I still have puppy energy at times and will get the zoomies right after I eat a meal. I do get a bit mouthy (not mean) and jumpy with my human when I am excited, but I listen pretty well when you tell me "no" and if you ignore me, I lose interest. 

I am potty trained, crate trained and use the dog door like a champ, too! I enjoy walks and walk well on a leash. I would love to have a family that is active and can take me with them on all their adventures!! My family shouldn't have kids under 10 since I'm very food motivated and would happily relieve small children of their snacks. hee hee!

Would you be willing to be patient and kind, but also firm with me and give me my furever home for this new year we've started?? 
Pretty Please? Did I mention I love to cuddle and I'll even tilt my head in a cute way when you talk to me! I am being fostered in the Denver/Metro area, so fill out an application today! Visit www.elpasocountycanine.org

If you are interested in adopting, please visit our website and complete an adoption application at www.elpasocountycanine.org/adopt

animal.description:
Omar, who knows the name ""Goose"" now was in a home where he was very loved, and very spoiled. He went on several good walks a week and had a fenced back yard where he could sunbathe and run around. He also had his favorite lap to sit on (yes, that's right - this 65 pound dog knows a good lap to sit on when he sees it!). His owners have had some life changes and illnesses recently, which led Goose to get less of his walks and less attention. This needy guy really wanted someone to play with, and figured out how to hop over his chainlink fence. This was a huge cause for concern due to being located near a busy highway. This big, goofy guy loves running, so he really needs a secure privacy fenced backyard, or a nice farm, in order to be his happiest self. They did not want to bring him back, but knew it would be in his best interest to find a safe place for him to run and live life the way he enjoys it. 
That being said, his previous family had SO MANY good things to say about him!
Goose loves blankets, and loves to be wrapped up like a pup-burrito. He never had a single accident in the house - He will go to the door or pace the house when he needs to potty. He does not like cats or small dogs and cannot live with them, however, he loves the company of dogs his size and will play with them! Goose can go on walks or runs for hours. He would make a wonderful hiking companion! Goose knows the commands sit, stay, lay, and come. He enjoys car rides and usually ends up napping during them. He loves sleeping in bed with his people (and he's been known to be a bit of a bed hog). Goose is the PERFECT family dog and loves children of all ages, although he can be pretty excitable and knock small children over. He has been around livestock of all kinds and looks at them like friends instead of snacks! We know that thunderstorms scare him and he likes to be with his people or in a kennel when there is one happening. 

We have estimated that Goose was born 03/01/2017 , and he currently weighs 65lbs....All pets have lifetime sanctuary at Haven of the Ozarks. If they cannot remain with their adopter, they must be returned to the Haven.

Adoption fees are as follows: 
Puppies under the age of 6 months - $125
Dogs weighing 30 pounds and less - $125 
Dogs ages 6 months to 5 yrs old - $90
Dogs over the age of 5 yrs old - $75.
Cats under the age of 6 months old - $75
Cats over the age of 6 months old - $65

animal.description:
*Due to concerns surrounding COVID-19, we have reformatted the way that we do adoptions in order to follow social distancing protocols. We are thrilled that so many people want to adopt right now, but we are not equipped to handle the large number of calls, applications, and email inquiries we are receiving. We are no longer answering phone calls and are doing all communications with adopters via email. If you have a dog you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application before sending us emails. When your application has been processed, you will receive an email from us with further instructions on how to adopt. You do not need a new application for every dog that you are interested in adopting. 

At MAMCO we understand that in order to continue rescuing moms and babies, we must stretch our finances as far as we are able. For this reason we use variable adoption pricing. By assigning higher adoption fees to high demand moms and puppies, we are able to rescue more families in need.The money raised through these adoptions acts as a benefactor to moms and puppies in our care who require expensive veterinary treatments, have behavioral issues, or need more time to find a home. We often reduce the adoption fees on these harder-to-place moms and puppies to help them find forever families. Adoption fees vary, but all include spay or neuter, microchip, up to date vaccinations and deworming, rabies vaccine at the time of spay or neuter, and 30 days of pet insurance. We also cover hernia repair and cherry eye repair at the time of spay or neuter. Applications can be filled out at mamcorescue.org.

animal.description:
Edna

 

Located in Sidney NE area

Schnauzer mix

9-11 years old ish 

Dog friendly with slow intros but would do best with dogs that mind their own business

No idea how she is with cats 

No young kids, she's a senior she doesn't deserve that 

House trained

Crate trained and knows some basic commands

Vision issues due to age

Hearing issues due to age

Needs spayed once ok'd by our vet, other than that she's good to go 

15lbs

 

Edna is an absolutely adorable little senior who is looking for a calm retirement home. She was found by an animal lover wandering around a west Texas city. Due to being recently groomed the finder expected to locate her family quickly. Unfortunately that didn't happen. Despite having a microchip it wasn't registered and the shelter that inserted the chip had no records at this point of who she was chipped by. The shelters , groomers, vets were all notified that she had been found. She has waited 2 weeks to be claimed to no avail. Now she's headed up us to find her next family! 

If you can help her please content us ASAP!

 $150.00 Adoption Fee 

(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

To Contact Us

Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org

Message the Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/HighPlainsPAW

Fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/adoption-application

Fill out our Foster Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/foster-application

Email us at highplainspaw@gmail.com

Call our VOICEMAIL at (402)957-1578

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!

animal.description:
Nicky and Millie were found locked in a chicken coop being abused by their owner. The 11 year old child within the home took it upon himself to reach out to a woman within the rescue world to tell her that as much as he loved his puppies, he needed her to save them from his father. Because of that brave young boy, Nicky and Millie have known nothing but safety, love and warmth for the past few months. Nicky and Millie have a very special bond experiencing what they have as brother and sister, therefore we will be adopting them as a bonded pair.

 Millie is extremely smart, obervant and loves to cuddle. She is roughly 9 months old, 9 lbs and we believe she is a chihuahua/terrier mix (but as with any rescue, it's always a best guess). Millie is excellent on the leash and she definitely wants to be the boss and can have a little bit of a Diva attitude which gives her some character! Millie has been working very hard in her foster home and her foster tells us that she is completely potty trained. 

Both Nicky and Millie are being fostered in Sonoma County, 95403. They have been doing fabulously in their foster home and have settled in very nicely. They are currently being fostered with children, and do to their size we will adopt them to a home with children 5 and older.

If you are interested, please fill out an application and send all supporting documentation.

You can find the application at www.softpawsrescue.org/applytoadopt (if you're unable to fill out the PDF, please print it out, fill it out and take pictures)

Additionally, pictures of the inside of your home (not just one room, but any place the dog might be), as well as your front and back yards

animal.description:
Name: Lilac (Female)
Breed: Pointer mix
Adoptable in: MA, RI, NH, CT, and VT

Good with dogs: Yes, with proper intros
Good with cats: No
Good with kids: No
Crate trained: Yes
House trained: Yes

Lilac is a sweet, lazy girl who is looking for a quiet home where she can play some fetch and then curl up in the dog bed and take a nap (her two favorite things). Lilac is wonderful with other dogs when properly introduced, and she loves to play. She would love a fenced yard to romp in. She can be leash reactive to new dogs, and though she has improved with training, this will always be something she needs to work on. For this reason, proper intros are a must with her. She is also ecollar trained. so her perfect home would continue this training with her. She excels with structure and routine.

Where Lilac still struggles greatly is with meeting new people in the home. Outside the home, and even a the vet, she is generally fine. When people that she does not know very very well come into the home, Lilac should be crated, leashed, or muzzled. She needs to be slowly introduced to new people, but once she gets to know you very very well, she's all in and is the kissiest, snuggliest girl. She is even very sweet to pretty much everyone while muzzled, so that's an easy fix to keep her safe. When people she does not know come into the home, she has an angry bark/growl but when introduced while muzzled she does fine. Because of her reactivity to new people, a single family home is the best fit for her. She would not do well in an apartment. Lilac has had a long road, and while she has come a long way, she is very much still a work in progress. With the right family she will do just fine.

Lilac's issues have happened in the past when her intros to new people coming into the home were not controlled (once, my contractor came in my back door while we were in the living room, and another time, my dog walker let her out of her crate after I advised her not to). So I can't emphasize enough that she needs to take it slow with new people :) But she will reward you for sure once you get to know her.

Age: 6 years
Weight: 45 lbs

Please Note: All dogs are posted until they are officially adopted. This dog may have other interested adopters in line. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application on our website at http://www.lasthopek9.org/ 

Questions? Please email adoptions@lasthopek9.org. For more photos, or information on upcoming adoption events where you can meet me, please go to www.lasthopek9.org or go to our Facebook page. Thank you for your interest in saving a life!

animal.description: This pretty girl's name is Esperanza! Esperanza's interests include going for walks, swimming, fetch, treats, toys and most of all, just unconditionally loving her people. On walks, Esperanza loves to feel and smell the fresh air, and finds so much joy in seeing and meeting new people. Esperanza is learning how to play with a variety of toys, and she loves to play fetch and puzzle games. Esperanza is exceptionally smart, and she is always eager to learn more fun games, as long as it means she gets to spend quality time with you. Esperanza's joyful and happy personality bursts through the walls when it's time for breakfast or dinner. She will dance for her food on her hind legs, fold her paws like a pterodactyl, and then patiently wait for you once you put her bowl of food down, to say 'wait. You will see her drooling after about 10 seconds of waiting. As much energy as Esperanza can have at moments, she's a pro at hanging out on the couch and cuddling under the blankets (especially underneath the blanket) with you watching a movie or TV. You should fully expect to share your movie popcorn with Esperanza, she loves to catch the popcorn when you toss them in the air. Esperanza would be a great addition to a family with no pets, or to someone who is looking for a pet as a companion. Esperanza has so much love to give, but would prefer to be the solo pet in the house. Esperanza would love to meet you and accompany you on a walk to show you how easy she is to please! Come meet her today!
