animal.description:
Hi, my name is Toby. I'm about 10-11 months old, and my foster mom thinks I'm mostly an English Pointer with maybe some Border Collie or Lab mixed in. I'm neutered, heartworm negative, and up to date on vaccinations. I currently live with other dogs and cats and get along well with them. I'm an active boy, curious about everything, and I've enjoyed the few car rides I've been on. I love walks outside, and I'm currently working on leash training and potty training as well as learning how to sit and stay. I am crate trained and don't have accidents in my crate ever. Chew toys are the best and I have never chewed on anything in the house but my toys. 

Because of my breed, age, and personality, I like to have a lot of stimulation and attention. With some training, I'd probably be a good camping or jogging buddy- I'd just really like to have a mom or dad that has an active lifestyle that I can be a part of. I'm nervous when I meet new people so I bark at them and that makes me look a little intimidating, but I warm up fairly quickly and I'm young enough that I can learn to overcome this behavior with some patience and socialization training.

If you are interested in giving Toby a forever home, please visit the link below to fill out an application! http://fureverafterrescue.org/adoption-application.html It is best to submit an application through a computer. We have experienced some problems when applications have been submitted using a mobile device. *When you submit the application, you are not obligated to adopt however it does reserve for you the opportunity to adopt that particular animal. We review them on a first come first served basis. If your application is approved, we will contact you and allow you the opportunity to adopt. If you choose not to adopt, we will contact the next approved applicant. If you have any questions or difficulties, please contact us and we will be glad to help!

animal.description:
Belle is currently fostered in Mentor Ohio, and her adoption fee/donation is $300

Belle is a beautiful 5-6 yr old female cocker spaniel.
She was surrendered to us due to her alpha personality with other dogs, and her separation anxiety.

Belle will need a special home, one where she is the only dog, and where someone is home during the day.
She will fight with select other dogs, especially females. She has severe separation anxiety so she doesn't do well when left alone.

Here is a note from her foster.....

Belle (AKA Bella) is a rambunctious personality and needs to maintain her interaction with her human(s) all the time. She is on high alert for doorbells, trucks & cars going by and geese and ducks in the yard.
She is very anxious while walking and goes back and forth in front of the person walking her. She does well in the back yard away from road noises. She travels in the car well. She responds well to calming commands and enjoys a treat for good behavior. Belle sleeps in a large crate with her blanket and a bed she sleeps well through the night. Belle needs to sleep in the same room with her human. She does not like to be alone during the day or night. She can work her cage open when anxious and will roam
anxiously and unhappily through the house. She will need a warm loving person familiar with the personality of cockers.

She is spayed and up to date on vaccines and micro chipped

If you would like to adopt Belle or would like more information on her, please fill out an adoption application
We do not have a shelter, all rescues are in foster homes - Dogs are not shown without first being approved to adopt.
Complete an Adoption Application Here
www.cherishedcockers.org/adoptionapp.htm
If you have any questions, please E-mail Cherished Cockers Rescue
Adoption Donation (vet bill-expenses), Home Visit, Adoption Contract, References Required.
We do not ship dogs.Pet needs to be picked up at foster home.In some cases we may be able to assist with transport. 
We would love to have more foster volunteers so we can rescue and rehome more cocker spaniels. If you are interested in fostering or learning more about it, please complete a Foster Application Here and one of our wonderful volunteers will be in touch!
www.cherishedcockers.org/foster.htm
For more information Cherished Cockers Rescue
www.cherishedcockers.org

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Ezra! He is an absolute rock star and one heck of a fighter! Born around December 2016, he weighs 80 pounds and could stand to gain another 10 or so.

Ezra came to SPIN in early December 2020 when a good Samaritan found him on the side of the road. Someone had shot him and left him to die. After lots of around the clock veterinary care and lots of love and support from his foster family, Ezra made a full recovery. Just a few days later, he managed to rip out his stitches from his neuter surgery, so back to the ER and back in a cone he went.

Now after five weeks of cones, and rest, and a really good grooming, Ezra is ready for his big debut!

Sweet Ezra and has never met dog or human he doesn't like! However, he isn't a fan of chickens or cats.

He loves, loves, loves toys! Ezra is the Pyrfect kind of Pyr, because he would do excellent in either a home with other doggos to play with or in a home as an only pup.

He is house trained, crate trained, does fantastic in a car. He is okay on leash and could use more practice. He is very vocal and loves letting his voice be heard.

Despite being dealt a pretty crummy hand to life in the beginning, Ezra is nothing but a bundle of joy and happiness, and he finds adorable ways to show he is grateful for his new lease on life.

Have we mentioned the Pyr paw? We're pretty sure this kid wrote the book on it.

Ezra is so dreamy with his medium length super soft fur and paw-some patches of unique coloring. He is blind in one eye, but it doesn't seem to bother him at all.

If you're looking for the most humble, adorable, and youthful pup, Ezra might be your guy!

SPIN Pyrs are all in foster homes in the Dallas/Fort Worth area. Potential adopters are asked to make travel arrangements if they live elsewhere. All SPIN dogs are spayed or neutered, current on vaccinations and on heartworm prevention. Please go to our website www.SpinRescue.org and fill out an application for this great Great Pyrenees!

animal.description:
King Kong is a 1 year old dog who is hoping to find his forever home.  This energetic boy wants to play and run with people.  Unfortunately when he came to Hopeful Tails, he was restricted from this since he was heartworm positive.  He has completed his treatment and finally can enjoy life.  When he first meets someone, he will roll on his back so you can scratch his stomach.  Pick up a toy and he's ready for a game of fetch.  Want to walk? King Kong will excitedly join you.  His personality will have you smiling and laughing all day.  King Kong wants all the love and attention though, he needs to be the only dog in a home. Additionally, we recommend a home with older (12 yrs. +)  or no kids. Currently, King Kong weighs 45 lbs.

Our loving boy’s adoption fee is $300 which includes his neuter, microchip implant, fecal exam, and shots up to date. 

Please consider opening your heart and loving home to this amazing pup. King Kong is so worth it.

Note:

All dogs require a $100 training deposit. Once confirmation of the completion of a training class has been sent to the rescue, you will receive your deposit back in full.

As we are a rescue all of our adult dogs/puppies for adoption must be spayed or neutered. Although we make every attempt to have this done before finding their adoptive families, this is not always possible. Please speak with your adoption coordinator to see of this service has already been performed or they will explain to you if your new dog/puppy will need this service while in your care at no cost to you.

When emailing please include your phone number to help speed up the adoption process.   Also, for the safety of our dogs we only adopt within a 2 hour radius of Joliet, Illinois to allow our volunteers to do home checks if necessary.

animal.description:
Looks like: Dachshund / Terrier Mix
Female, 5 years old, 11 pounds
Sunny Delight had a rough start, but she has blossomed in her foster home and is a happy dog when she is home with the people she trusts. In her foster home she has joyous, bouncy energy and her tail wags constantly. It does take her some time before she trusts people, so she would do best in a quiet home with a patient adopter who will let her progress and trust at her own pace. This is very important for her. If you push her too quickly, she'll lose the trust in people that her foster family has worked so hard to earn. 

She does trust females more readily than males, which is often the case with shy dogs. 

She still gets worried if either of her foster parents approach her or try to initiate a pet or touch, but she will allow affection when she's curled up in a bed or on the couch or if she goes to them for affection which is starting to happen little by little. Interactions need to be initiated by her. She does enjoy being by her person and hanging out wherever they are. 

She gets along fine with other dogs, and we think she'd be fine in a home with cats. She'd be a great buddy for another dog. She can be playful if they want to play, and is also happy to snuggle up to another dog and take a nap. 

She is very quiet, polite, sleeps through the night and is house trained. Riding in a car stresses her out at this point. Having a secure yard is important for Sunny. Her potty routine is made much easier and less stressful on everyone involved if they there is a secure yard she can access. 

Sunny Delight was found by animal control with a stillborn puppy hanging out of her and she had more stillborn puppies inside. She was taken to Hitchcock Road Animal Services. They were able to get her to a veterinarian for a c-section and to be treated for sepsis. It was touch and go, but she survived. She went through a deep depression after losing her puppies. 

We believe she lived on the streets fending for herself for quite a while or was very under socialized in a previous home because of her semi-feral nature. With all she has been through, she has never shown any sign of aggression. She really wants to trust people and to love and be loved. It will just take her some time and patience.
animal.name: Sunny Delight

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

For additional photos and video of Krissy, please visit our website at myaarf.org.

Krissy is a very loving dog and wants your approval and affection. She also loves to play with toys and will almost fetch.....she goes after the toy but hasn't brought it back just yet. We are sure she could get the gist of it with some training and encouragement. Krissy also recently conquered stairs for the first time at her foster family's house and is settling in well. The adorable video of her foster family cheering her on as she conquers the stairs is available on our website.

Krissy is a high energy dog and can get easily excited so we recommend older children in the home. This is only because she may accidentally knock over a little one with her excitement. Krissy is completely house trained and crate trained and walks fairly well on a leash - sometimes things outdoors can be distracting! Krissy gets along well with other dogs and loves to engage and play, but some dogs may not love her higher energy level. She has a high prey drive, so we do not recommend a home with cats or other small animals. Krissy just needs the right family to give her the love and training she needs and she will return your love tenfold. If you think Krissy may be a good fit for you and your home, please read the paragraph below in its entirety.

As a purely foster based rescue, we have no central location where you can visit our dogs. Therefore, we only honor meet requests from pre-approved adopters, with an application on file. Please fill in our online adoption application at www.myaarf.org as fully as you can and allow at least 24-48 hours for a response from our busy volunteers. Our adoption fee is $450 which includes all transport, vetting, and micro-chipping. *Proof of completion of obedience training within 90 days of adoption is a requirement for adoption through AARF.*

animal.description:
Breed: Tibetan Terrier - DNA test confirmed it!
Age: Senior
Sex: Neutered male
Weight: 20 pounds

Max came into foster care due to some unfortunate circumstances. His owner became ill and could no longer care for him. He adjusted really well into his new foster home. Max is playful, affectionate, and Yes he is a terrier, into a little mischief.....He LOVES to be with people, and will even follow you into the bathroom! He gets along with other dogs, no issues.

We were hoping to get Max a much needed dental, but pre-dental Labs were concerning. So instead of having a dental Max has gone through a number of test/ procedures, trying to figure out what is going on internally.

So far, testing is showing acute kidney disease. Max is now on special food with hopes of slowing down this chronic disease. There are other concerning Labs, we are now starting an antibiotic to fight a possible infection.

We realize with all of Max’s medical issues it will take a special home to adopt him and give him the medical care he needs. We are hopeful there is someone who loves the Tibetan breed or who has had a similar experience with their personal dog that would be willing to give Max a chance.

Please let us know if you have any specific questions about Maxwell or if you would be willing to donate funds on his behalf.
You can send money via paypal to apbpets@schnauzerama.org or mail a donation to: Animal Placement Bureau, P. O. Box 80146, Lansing, MI 48908-0146

If you have any questions, please email tzupoomom@gmail.com .
You can find our application at http://apbdogs.org/apply-for-adoption/

Animal Placement Bureau's standard adoption fee is $250 but is negotiable for Senior dogs. All dogs are spayed or neutered, updated on required vaccinations, tested for heart worm and many receive dental cleanings. 

Our adoption process includes an application, personal and vet reference checks, and a home visit. We do not ship dogs under any circumstances.  
We do not have a facility; all of our dogs are fostered in private homes.  Appointments to visit our dogs are only available after an application has been filled out, and processing has begun.
Please be kind to our volunteers. E-mail inquiries will be answered much faster than phone inquiries; our phone number is a voice mailbox only. 
If you'd like to apply to adopt one of our dogs, please fill out the online application at http://apbdogs.org/apply-for-adoption/.

animal.description:
*******Please read post fully before responding, we greatly appreciate any and all interest in this wonderful girl, but if you see this post, please assume she is still available and do not respond asking just that-lol-most rescue's get an incredible amount of emails about each dog and just do not have enough time to engage and seek information from sparse responses. We have applications at sparrowdogs.com, and please tell us a little about yourself, that helps. We want to make the very best fit not just for Ella but her future family as well :) !!****************

   EllaBella, that has become this big goofballs nickname. We really just call her "Ella", but when she is really silly, or perhaps naughty, she gets the EllaBella. Ella is just 2 years old and has had a bumpy past. We know that she was adopted from a shelter and did not do well with the toddler in the house, hence, no small children.  It is stressful for a dog to be around children/infants, I cannot blame Ella, just was not the right home, many dogs just are not comfortable around the little ones( many people too, lol!!)  She is also potty trained, non-destructive and knows basic commands. 

Ella is a very outdoorsy girl. This recent snowfall made her day!!  We have been out running, playing, throwing snowballs and going for a big walk. EllaBella had to climb up every snow bank the plow made.  She is such a happy girl and she does know basic commands. BUT...she does need a dog savvy family/person.  She needs a (as Cesar Milan would say) a calm, assertive person in her life. IF you are not in charge, well guess who will take over??  So many super intelligent breeds are like that, they will be your best friend and right hand man, but if you can't lead the pack, they will take over. 

Ella will do well with some basic training classes, perhaps some agility, talk about channeling that energy and athleticism. She wants to please, snuggle, love and be a huge part of your life. I know there is that special someone out there for this most perfect girl. We think she is pretty darn awesome!

 She can be a little shy meeting new people, that is expected after all the recent transitions, but she is truly one in a million!!  Her adoption fee is $300, she is fully vetted, the adoption fee is tax deductible, and she will go home with plenty of supplies to help her settle in. Please email Kristine at joysparrows@gmail.com.  (Please NO phone calls)  EllaBella is 2 years old and 60 pounds.

animal.description:
Wayland is the spunky life of the party! This girl is curious and always likes to see what's going on. Wayland acts like a puppy. She loves playing with her squeaky toys, rope toys, or wrestling with her canine companions. She is most comfortable when she has one or two other dogs around. She can sometimes take a few minutes to warm up to a new person, but her curiosity gets the best of her and she can't help but come say hello! She is a very sweet, good dog that would make an awesome addition to someone's family.

Wayland has some typical cattle dog traits like nipping, but she doesn't mean any ill-will. She thinks she is playing and is gentle about it! Because of this, young children may not be suitable for her unless they are used to this behavior. She is learning how to walk on a leash and learning basic commands. She is a smart girl and will do anything for a treat!

Wayland is only available for foster-to-adopt at this time. She is heartworm positive and will need to get started on her treatment soon. All medical expenses are taken care of by the rescue when the dog is in foster-to-adopt care. Wayland will have no lasting health issues as a result of her heartworm status. She will be a normal, healthy young dog!

animal.description:
Val
2yr old Mastiff/Boxer mix

Hi there, I’m Val! I’m so excited to meet you! I get excited a lot and I can hardly contain myself! It must be the boxer in me, we boxer mixes have lots and lots of energy! 
I came to rescue a month ago and now I’m ready to find my forever home! Boy oh boy am I excited! When I first came to rescue, I was so happy to be back in a home I couldn’t stop running around and bouncing all over the place. I love couches and fireplaces and cozy dog beds to sleep on and humans to cuddle. More than comfy things, I love LOVE food. If you got a treat I’ll listen! That’s how my family is training me because no one taught me how to have manners. When I first got to my foster home, I was very excited and jumped, mouthed, and tugged on her clothes… a lot. I did not know how to act politely when I wanted something and sometimes, I could be a little rude about it. It took some work to teach me that I’m not a puppy anymore (I’m 2!) and I’m too big for that behavior. I have gotten much better, but I still do get myself all excited sometimes and need reminders to use my inside manners. My foster mom says I can be fairly stubborn and I don’t always like to listen. I don’t think I’m stubborn, I’m just a diva and I know what I want! Because of these traits and the manners I am working on,  I should not be in a home with kids. My new family should understand energetic breeds and have experience training and managing stronger, more… *ahem*…. diva like dogs. 
I have learned some very good habits though! I am very good in my crate, sometimes I even put myself to bed at night. I know I can’t go to the bathroom in the house and I’ll ask to go outside. I am very food motivated and like to learn new things and my foster mom keeps working with me. The things I’m best at though are being goofy to make you laugh and loving you to pieces! I enjoy snuggles and attention and just want to be close to my family and know where they are. Once I am attached to my people, I will be so loyal to them and love them forever and ever. I’m a very sweet girl and just want lots of love and affection and I’m not afraid to ask for it! Sometimes I can be a bit vocal when I want something and I will make all sorts of funny noises until you listen to what I have to say. I am learning I have an inside voice but sometimes I don’t want to use it so maybe a detached house is best for me. I also love to run around and get out my zoomies and bounces so a fenced yard to do that would be important. Did I tell you I LOVE ball? I listen to my mom for a ball almost as well as I do for food! I love playing fetch and I don’t seem to ever get tired of it. I really like playing with other dogs too! I love to meet them on walks and I have fun play dates with other dogs. I would be okay in a home with another dog if it was the right dog. Sometimes I don’t like to share and I am learning that’s not very nice and I have to be more polite. I do apologise to my friends with kisses and more play once when I’m told I have to share. I do have a cat foster brother and I really really just want to be his friend and play with him! He doesn’t like me much though. I am better at giving him his space but sometimes I like to try and get him to play still. 
There is one other important thing you should know about me. I have an enlarged heart and a grade four heart murmur. This puts me at a greater risk for heart failure later in my life. Don’t be sad though! You would not know this by looking at me! I don’t let it get in my way. Right now, I’m living my best life playing and getting lots of walks and exercise. My heart is good and I do not show any signs of heart failure. It just means that down the road I might need some medication and I should go for annual check-ups to make sure everything is in working order. 
My foster mom says I’m a very sweet and fun girl with a big personality that will make you laugh. She says I’m a good girl and will find the perfect family to help me be my best self. I realise I have a bit of a big list of requirements for my new home, but for those that have a soft spot for goofy, loyal, loving and energetic dogs with a personality you will not be disappointed. I will be the first to give you kisses in the morning, the first to make you laugh, the first to great you when you get home and the last to cuddle you at night. I am really looking forward to meeting you! 
Vap has been vaccinated,  microchipped, dewormed, heartworm tested, spayed, treated with Advantage, and has had ultra sound done on her heart. It is reccomended that her future home follow up in 1yrs time for another ultra sound to ensure nothing has changed. 
Val came to us as an unclaimed stray from LACC. 

The adoption fee is $600 and includes spay/neuter (dogs over 6 months), vaccines, heartworm test (dogs over 6 months), deworming, Flea and tick prevention and microchip. Please visit www.paws-united.com to fill out an application.
**For puppies under 6 months a $200 spay/neuter rebate will be given with proof of spay/neuter certificate signed by a vet, if they have not been done prior to adoption.**
**Please note we DO NOT adopt our dogs as outdoor/farm dogs. These dogs are coming to us as stray, roaming or dogs that have lived a life tied to a chain. Our goal is to bring them in the house off the chain and give them a pampered indoor dogs lifestyle. Unless otherwise stated we will not even consider a home that has intentions of leaving our dogs outdoors or tied to a chain**

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at DenaE@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Lunagirl
Estimated Breed : Red Heeler Cattle Dog Mix
Approximate Age: 8 months
Approximate Weight: approx. 35 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
This sweetie is looking for an active home with lots of space to run. She is friendly, but still very young and has a lot to learn. Luna is a super sweet, energetic dog who will make a family or person very happy. She does great with other dogs and loves people. She does jump up for attention, so small kids might unintentionally get knocked over, but with training she could definitely do-exist with small kids. She loves to crawl into your lap for attention as well, so is capable of taking it easy as well. If you have to the time to train and energy to keep up with her high energy lifestyle, please apply!
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

PLEASE NOTE: GPMR communicates primarily by email. If you have any questions regarding one of our Mastiffs, please read their bio and if you still have questions- drop us an email at info@greatplainsmastiffrescue.org . If you have questions about our adoption procedures, please go to our Pages of Interest on the left hand column under 'Adoption Info.' We answer email inquiries almost immediately-usually always within a few hours and phone calls are returned with 24-36 hours.

GPMR does not have a shelter. All of our dogs are kept in loving foster homes. We must have a completed adoption
application on file before meeting any of our mastiffs.

GPMR adopts to the states of Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas, Arkansas, Missouri, Louisiana and parts of Colorado.
!!!Any mastiffs being adopted out of the state of Oklahoma require a health certificate to be paid for by the adopter!!!

Meet Otis! This sweet boy came to GPMR from a family that loves him very much but could no longer keep him. They described him as the perfect family dog. The day we met him, we knew how hard it was for them to let go because they were right, he is perfect! He is good with kids and other dogs, we were told he is scared of cats!Although he is the size and stocky build of a Bullmastiff, he has a handsome English Mastiff face and temperament. He has a vibrant apricot coat with pitch black markings. In addition to being stunningly beautiful, Otis is healthy! He was treated for ear infections (his owner said he gets these on/off) and will need routine ear rinses to maintain healthy ears. But unlike a lot of dogs, Otis will sit still and let you take care of him. At 7 years old, he is very docile and calm. He enjoys napping near people and will play in short bursts followed by more napping. Otis is polite and obedient. He rarely barks and is house trained. He has free roam of the house when left, he's never been destructive.If you've been looking for a rescue dog that has a known background and doesn't come with baggage, meet Otis. He is already a great pet, he just needs a new home. He would be a great dog for a first time Mastiff owner!Otis is being fostered in Yukon, OK.Save a Mastiff...Adopt, Foster, Volunteer!

animal.description:
Listo (pronounced LEE-stow) is a super sweet, loving 7 year old, 32 lb. Australian cattle dog. He is highly active and intelligent, extremely loyal, and is considered a “velcro” dog. He is always curious to know what his owners are up to and needs to be right where the action is. However, he does have a lot of anxiety in certain situations, and is protective of his home when strangers first enter his house or property. When he feels comfortable and safe, Listo is THE best dog. His joy is in pleasing his people. This boy needs an adults only home (no children), in a quiet setting. Listo is not good with cats, but he may be ok living with an easy going, calm, respectful dog, who will not get in his face. 

Listo is a happy boy, who has a lot of personality, somewhere between being almost human and a silly cartoon character. He is extremely food motivated, and an eager helper in the kitchen. He is generally chill around a quiet house, and loves to cuddle. In the morning, he shows his love by waiting for his people to stir, and will crawl up to snuggle into you. A long morning walk is next in his daily routine. Listo rides well in a car, and is completely housebroken.

As an energetic guy with an active brain he needs to be exercised every day, and usually walks five miles each day. He enjoys being on the move and loves working/training and learning new tricks. Listo looks forward to his training sessions each evening. He needs to routinely work for treats in order to help keep his mind stimulated. As a result, Listo is a highly trained dog who knows several commands.

Listo loves long walks and is always up for hiking, walking on the beach, and generally being outdoors. He walks well on leash and when in public, he is excited to meet new people and will run up to greet them. On walks, he minds his own business and does not react to other dogs. If off-leash in a park or beach, he enjoys a quick greeting other dogs before running to keep up with his people. If allowed to play with other dogs, Listo will use herding moves, circling and going for their feet, which may annoy some dogs. The only dogs he will react badly to are German Shepherds. Listo once had a bad encounter with a German Shepherd, and now becomes alarmed and very upset when he sees one, often growling, barking and pulling.

Listo’s Story (by his current people):
Listo has been through a lot. We rescued him when he was around 1.5 years old, after he was found as a stray in Oklahoma. It was apparent from the beginning that Listo had anxiety and had difficultly calming down and focusing when triggers (loud noises, garbage trucks, skateboards, etc.) were present. This manifested through barking, pacing constantly, and occasional urinary incontinence. Listo was able to overcome all of this, after a great deal of time, training, patience, and love. He is a graduate of various manners and agility classes.

Part of his journey included consults with a behavior specialist at the San Francisco SPCA, after behavior modification training was only able to take him so far. Working closely with the specialist, it ultimately decided that Listo would be best suited for a medication (along with continued training). He has been on daily doses of Clomicalm for just over 4 years and is now able to refocus even when most triggers are present. Also, he no longer has urinary incontinence issues. Listo consistently shows us that he is highly trainable as we are always working with him on new tricks and behavior changes. 

In 2019, an eye specialist observed that Listo's vision was diminishing due to a hereditary condition and that eventually he would be blind. It is estimated that he can see about 50% currently, but he is very smart and adaptable to his surroundings. He has no problem navigating areas that are well lit and areas that he is familiar with. His diminishing vision may cause him to react to unknown people coming into his home, and be hesitant in new places/situations. 

Likely due to his poor vision and being unfamiliar with children, in January he unexpectedly and unprompted lunged and bit at the feet of a 6 year old in rubber boots who was visiting in our yard. Fortunately the child was okay. He has also nipped at the heels of several adult guests in our home in the past couple of years, who Listo did not know well. This nipping behavior was not present during the first couple years with Listo, but it developed over time.  With people his negative reaction seems to be triggered if they are wearing boots or baggy pants. He also barks and paces when guests arrive at the house and has difficulty calming down. We were working with a trainer in our home in early 2020 to address these issues, but due to the pandemic, were unable to continue training at home. As we have not had guests in the last year due to COVID, we have not been able to address this more recent behavior. Additionally, the recent birth of our son has caused an increase in anxiety for Listo at home as well as overprotective behavior. 

We are hoping that Listo can find a quiet home with adventurous owners who will enjoy exercising and working with him daily, where the owners understand the needs of not only a cattle dog but a pup with special needs, and are adaptable to his vision loss. As with all cattle dogs, ongoing training with positive reinforcement, exercise, and stimulation are necessary for him to have a happy, healthy life. He is abundantly loving and he will always be by your side and would love to provide companionship to someone who can dedicate time to his needs. For all the reasons above, Listo needs a calm home in a quiet, non-urban, area.

If you are interested in meeting LIsto, please contact us for our updated adoption form, by emailing us at:  doghouse@hittgv.org  or download, print and complete the form at: http://hittgv.org/index.php/adopt. If you have questions, please leave a message at (707) 583-9583.

George is a 9-week-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, and spayed/neutered. This puppy is currently in foster care learning home etiquette, kennel training, and housebreaking. We would love for you to meet this puppy and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

Bill is a 9-week-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, and spayed/neutered. This puppy is currently in foster care learning home etiquette, kennel training, and housebreaking. We would love for you to meet this puppy and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
Until last week, Nita’s life was one living chained to a post in a dirt lot with nothing more than a dog house. Her life was watching as everyone else lived. Once in a while she would get to go out with her owner to inspect his grounds, but the rest of her time was just watching. When her owner died, she waited for two more months, chained to that same post, with only her dog house, waiting for someone to come.

Nita was lucky. She didn’t know it, but she had a friend who found out what was going on and was determined to help her. He began reaching out, looking for help. In the meanwhile, he brought blankets for her house, as the weather was getting colder at nights. He even brought a leash to take her out for walks and get her used to walking. Whenever her new friend would come, she would jump for joy. And then, one day he brought his dog, just to see how she would be with a furry friend. Nita’s entire body wagged back and forth, sniff, sniff, sniff. You would have thought she were in heaven to be able to see another dog.

The morning we heard of Nita, we couldn’t let her wait another day. One of our volunteers picked her up and made the long trek down to Coastal’s new home. She was so happy to be with people. More than anything, she was happy to be able to run without the quick yank of the chain that had stopped her for so many years. One thing we have noticed about this sweet little girl, she is grateful for every moment of attention, for every touch of the hand. She is grateful for every meal she gets, and she is so grateful to not be alone.

Today Nita gets to spend time walking with the volunteers. She can be a strong little girl, and she’s not yet used to walking by your side. Everywhere she looks, there is something new, and she wants to soak in every little thing. For a dog who has been deprived of so much, her personality shows just what kind of survivor she is. We are so happy that we were able to rescue her.  One day, her fur will shine like the diamond that she is, with the dirt lot underneath her feet and the dust in her eyes, a distant memory.
Please visit http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/ to learn more about our dogs. Click on available dogs to see further descriptions. If you are interested in me, please contact us at information@coastalgsrsd.org or call (858) 779-9149. Don't forget to fill out our online application:  http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/webform/1774/adoption-application.

The minimum adoption donation ranges from $300 to $400. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is 100% tax deductible.

Prior to placement, all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are usually microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis. Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems.

Our adoption process begins with completing an application on-line. A phone screening will soon follow, and lastly a home visit will be conducted by our volunteers.

animal.description:
Enzo is one of the unlucky puppies who was caught up in the trap of COVID.  His family loved him, but because of COVID, they weren’t able to get him the socialization that a young German Shepherd puppy needs more than anything.  When he became out of control, afraid of strangers and new things because of that lack of socialization, they called Coastal for help.  Meeting the volunteer who brought him to the rescue didn’t go very well for Enzo at first.  He was being handed off to a stranger, not knowing where he was going or what would happen to him.  Lucky for him, his volunteer angel was one who was not easily frightened by puppies, even if they were large with big teeth.  His family placed Enzo in the back of her car.  He filled the back seat, and she just waited for him to calm down, and then she got in the driver’s seat.  Enzo knew immediately just by her gentle but commanding words and her demeanor that she was in charge, and he knew he was safe.

He made the trek down to Coastal’s Ranch where he became overwhelmed again.  There were so many other dogs and more people than Enzo had ever seen.  To Enzo, the most important thing was to warn them to stay away so they wouldn’t hurt him.  Little did he know, no one, absolutely no one meant him any harm.  Enzo’s team was formed that day, three people at first.  He got to know them.  He would bark at first, but when he learned that he didn’t need to be afraid, his guard slowly began to come down.  Enzo’s leash was the key to making him feel safe.  Sadly, it was the only thing he had left that smelled like home, the one thing that reminded him of the family he once had.  His leash meant the world to him, and we made sure it was close to him at all times.  He needed something to hold onto until he knew the bigger world was safe, until he knew that he was as special to his new friends as they would become to him.

The day we knew we broke the final wall with Enzo was the day we switched his leash and he paid no attention to the old.  He was no longer attached to the past but living in the moment and looking toward the future.  He began to recognize the friends that he had made, and when they would come to his yard he would watch them approach and then slide his body sideways against the gate so they could pet him through the chain link.   He began to play bow and to run after his ball and do the puppy jumping for joy at the sight of his friends’ visits.  Most of all, he began to relax.

Since he’s been with us, Enzo has also made friends with other dogs and he really likes them.   He’s learning how to play with the innocence of a young puppy.  He would do well in a home with another dog who could help him with both his socialization and be a good playmate and companion for him.

Enzo is ready for his special forever home.  He has made great strides in his socialization and his trust, but he has to have a home that is dedicated to continuing that socialization.   Even though his circle of trust is larger and he has more friends, the big world is still a scary place for him; and for every step he has made forward, without continued work, it will all be lost.   Enzo needs a home that has experience with German Shepherds who are a bit behind in their socialization.  Enzo captures your heart with his soft eyes now, but we will always remember the lost, wandering eyes of the frightened puppy we first met, the scared boy who barked to keep everyone away, and we know we can’t lose sight of the special home that Enzo needs.  That is our promise to him.

This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is 100%25 tax deductible. animal.description:
Rainey is not like most dogs. She has lived an unsocial and difficult life, and it shows. Rainey was born inside of an abandoned trash hoarder's house. She was one of 43 other dogs that lived without humans other than a neighbor that would empty bags of kibble onto the porch for them. Rainey had never interacted with people and barely ever saw them until a rescue team came to save all the dogs from the house. Being brought into a real home with people for the first time at 2 years old was shocking for her.

Rainey has been in foster care since October 2020. When she first arrived, she was absolutely petrified and wanted to jump out of her skin. She hid in corners, cringed when touched, and did anything she could to get away from the people that she thought were going to hurt her. Though she didn't trust people, she never had a problem with any of the other dogs. Big or small, she likes them all. She likes to be surrounded by a pack. It makes her feel more confident.

Rainey has now learned that humans aren't bad and doesn't run when she sees people that she knows. She knows her routine and it helps her feel more confident. She knows her name and responds to it. Though Rainey still doesn't like to be touched, she can be leashed and walks well. She will follow you around from time to time and is curious of her surroundings. She wants to trust this new world, she just isn't completely sure of it yet.

Rainey is considered to be a feral dog. She will need someone that is extremely patient and understanding. She will likely never be a dog that enjoys being pet, that plays, or is comfortable around children. Her best home would be a homebody with other dogs and ample time to gain her trust. The trusting bond you build with a feral dog is unlike any other. It is special and worth the time! Rainey will wait patiently in foster care until her special human comes along.

Mickey is easy to leash but will pull hard to get out of the kennel because he just wants to GO! He knows "sit" for treats and takes them gently. Because Mickey is still like a puppy, he can be jumpy and mouthy because he is so energetic. He definitely needs training to learn his manners. He doesn't interact well with the dogs in their kennels in the shelter and will need a dog-to-dog introduction if an adopter already has a dog at home.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please Click Here to Fill Out an Online Adoption Application!
Aurora is a very pretty dog, with a very "typical" husky personality.
She can be a bit stubborn, does NOT like to be left alone, can be destructive if she gets bored, and is vocal if she is not with you due to separation anxiety.
She has also shown sings of "resource guarding" her things (like food/water/toys) from other dogs. She MUST be in a kennel or at a dog daycare and NEVER to be left alone in your home-She has eaten through doorways and window screens before when left alone for too long. Lesson Learned.

Aurora DOES have some amazing qualities though, so don't let all of that scare you away from wanting to adopt her!

Aurora loves ALL people and has a great demeanor around strangers. She loves to go on hikes/jogs/camping and doing anything outdoors!
She loves most other dogs, as long as they are not super invasive she has gotten along with everyone she has met so far. She seems to like other huskies best!
She has a very goofy playstyle, and booty-bumps her friends! Super silly!
She also know when it is time to relax, and once she is past her anxiety-phase of being in a new home, she settles down at night and is pretty easy-going!
She is great in the car, potty trained indoors from what we have seen, she is mostly crate trained to a plastic kennel (She is very vocal at first, but mellows out within 15-30 minutes.)
Getting better every day!!!

***Aurora is not downright mean to cats, she was actually raised around them, but has chased cats that ran from her outdoors and we would NOT want one to get hurt, so we ill not accept any applications with cats (or small critters like bunnies or chickens) in the home. ***
*** Aurora would NOT do well in a home with children under 16 years old. She can be nippy, jumpy, and protective over her food, water, and other items. We will not accept an application with children.

***COVID 19 NOVEMBER 2020 PROTOCOL***

Due to the surge of Covid 19 and statewide restrictions, we are adopting to LOCAL (CLALLAM AND JEFFERSON COUNTY) RESIDENTS ONLY. We are not doing adoptions to Canada at this time due to the border closure. We do not ship animals. 

OPHS is appointment only. All potential adopters must fill out an adoption application prior to setting up an appointment to meet the animal. An application can be found on our website  https://www.ophumanesociety.org/dog-adoption-application

NAME: Junior
AGE: About 4 years old
WEIGHT: About 63 lbs
BREED(S): Pit Bull
REASON FOR ARRIVAL: Owner surrender

GENERAL INFO ABOUT PERSONALITY:  Oh, sweet Junior!

Junior is an absolute gentleman when it comes to people! He loves giving and receiving affection, and is a GREAT loose leash walker! He doesn't react to other dogs on a walk as long as they don't get in his face. Junior has a fairly calm and mellow activity level, especially for a young-ish pittie!

Junior came to us after getting in a fight with a family member's dog. Junior has had a rough go of finding a forever home, as he was probably not well treated or socialized with animals as a pup, and bounced around from house to house.

Junior will need good quality food- like most pits, he can have a sensitive stomach and skin. We have found grain free salmon or lamb and rice to work the best. 

Junior would love to have a fenced yard of his own where he can play with his ball and not be bothered by other animals.

Additional BEHAVIOR notes: Only pet

animal.description:
Emmy is around a year and a half.   Emmy was abandoned, along with three other dogs, when her family moved.  Little did the shelter know, she was pregnant and very soon after gave birth.  She has spent the last couple of months caring for her babies and has done a wonderful job.  She is a great mom, but she is almost ready to go to a family of her own.  As one might guess, Emmy was very stressed being in a new and strange environment, with the lives of her puppies on her young shoulders.  She was very afraid of people.  Thankfully, she was welcomed into a foster home where her foster mom is very patient, and slowly, the walls are coming down for Emmy and she is learning to trust.  She was just introduced to her resident 4-legged companion, a wonderful German Shepherd.   Their first off leash encounter, it was chase, play, and chase.  Emmy is a mom, but she is very much still a puppy herself.  She needs a home with a very patient family, a family with another confident dog that can help her continue to come out of her shell.    She has been working on her potty training and is doing very well.  She sees her crate as her safe place to be.  Walking on a leash is something that is very new to her and her new family should be ready to take it in baby steps.   Emmy may take a while to warm up, but when she does, she loves to cuddle and snuggle.   She would love a family that can give her the time and space to learn that she is safe and has a family that she can trust.  She needs for her canine partner to be a playful one too.   She loves to play.

animal.description:
These sweet babies were surrendered to us last week. Two of their siblings have already been reserved but these 6 beauties are still available. They were born the day after Thanksgiving and are 8 weeks old now. All weigh between 18-22 lbs. We are unsure of the breed but these will be BIG dogs. They are all super friendly and playful. They are a little timid at first but quickly warm up and are good with other animals and kids They will be ready for adoption on 2/2 after they receive their second round of vaccines. These are gorgeous babies and won’t last long. Get your apps in on these big chunks of love. 

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Dunkin is an 9-week-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, and spayed/neutered. This puppy is currently in foster care learning home etiquette, kennel training, and housebreaking. We would love for you to meet this puppy and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
Nick:

The beautiful snowy white 2 yr old Nick is still looking for his forever home.  

Since being altered he is much calmer and less jumpy and in your face. He's a very big boy and could be difficult to handle. He still needs a strong, confident owner to help guide him to being the best boy he can be. He's still working on leash manners and if not corrected he will pull you all over the place. 

He's fantastic at fetch and will chase just about any toy but really loves jolly balls and being chased around with a toy in his mouth. He's very active and athletic and lots of fun to watch run around and play. He's very interactive and loves to he with his humans. He can he great with other dogs his size with a proper intro. He's still got a bit of dog on dog skills to learn and can be a bit dominant and use his paws so a well balanced dog to help guide him would be beneficial.  

His size, strength, and tendency to throw himself at you for a hug doesn't make him ideal for small children or those with elderly at home. However, he would be great with older kids or with training as he is very human friendly. He loves to ride in the car and prefers to have his head between the seats watching next to you if he can't ride shot gun. He is potty trained and not destructive that we've seen so far and he does kennel well.  

Think you're the family for Nick? Please reach out to us at www.vegasshepherdrescue.com

animal.description:
Are you a white German Shepherd enthusiast? Have you met Cooper?

Cooper was rescued from a shelter in Fresno, along with his partner and a 6 month old puppy. A few weeks earlier the entire family was left at the shelter, all 3 were sick and scared and trying hard to understand what they had done wrong. After a short stay at a veterinary hospital to treat for kennel cough and other common diseases of neglect, Cooper and his family were ready for adoption.

His partner and puppy found wonderful homes right away, but Cooper was too scared and depressed, and for a couple weeks he did not show well in adoption events. Luckily he was invited to join one of our foster homes where he had the attention and gentle care he needed to recover and develop confidence to be the wonderful dog that he is.

Cooper is a typical white German Shepherd! He is handsome, smart, curious, and very affectionate. He is also very strong and at times he can be stubborn. He has excellent house manners and adapted well to the family routine. His favorite pastime is fetching balls in the back yard and his level of energy is quite moderate. Cooper is dog friendly. He is respectful with the senior dogs in his foster home, and playful with the young ones. He gets along with both male and female dogs.

Cooper appreciates the humans who take care of him, and can be overprotective if not socialized. When adopted, his new family will need to keep working on his socialization. He is eager to please his handlers and will benefit from professional training.

His ideal home would have other dogs and he absolutely needs experienced handlers. Because of his tendency to overprotect his family we do not recommend him for a home with children.
Please visit http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/ to learn more about our dogs. Click on available dogs to see further descriptions. If you are interested in me, please contact us at information@coastalgsrsd.org or call (858) 779-9149. Don't forget to fill out our online application:  http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/webform/1774/adoption-application. The minimum adoption donation ranges from $300 to $400. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is 100%25 tax deductible. Prior to placement, all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are usually microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis. Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems. Our adoption process begins with completing an application on-line. A phone screening will soon follow, and lastly a home visit will be conducted by our volunteers.

animal.description:
Our gorgeous 2 yr old girl Karly is back through no fault of her own.  

These are tough times for humans and animals alike.  Poor Karly's humans lost their income and home and were forced to bring her back when they had to move and couldn't care for her.  

She was a very good girl in the home.  She loved her teenage human brother and dad very much and was always ready to snuggle or play.  She's an active girl who likes to play a little rough and can be mouthy at times.  She loves a good game of tug and will play a great round of fetch and even bring it to you most of the time.  She's potty trained and well behaved in the home when exercised.  

She doesn't love being in a kennel and can be destructive if given the opportunity.  Exercise will be important for this young, active, and athletic girl.  She's a good size and will need a confident, strong handler to be her best self.  Her dog relationships aren't always great and small dogs are a no for her.  She is picky about her friends but has potential for sure.  She loves most humans she meets but small children could be subjected to mouthiness and being knocked over by her strong energy and play.

animal.description:
Hudson recently came to VSR in partnership with another rescue partner and he's a fantastic example of his breed. 

At 2 years old he is still all playful quirky puppy and full of spit and vinegar.   He's vocal and fun and loves to play with his humans and get cuddles more than anything else.  He will run and chase and play and interact quite a bit.  He can be slightly mouthy when he gets overstimulated but not too hard. 

He's a quirky boy who will bark at reflections or shadows on the walls outside sometimes.  He has good house manners and is potty trained.  He's the tidiest boy we've had in awhile and keeps his kennel area spotless and doesn't even muss his blankets.  He is not destructive or anything of the sort and is a very good boy. 

He can be strange in his choosing of new humans and quirky about making friends.  Sometimes he's entirely open to it and sometimes he comes across as unfriendly at first.  He's a bit protective of his favorite humans and will guard if given the opportunity.  He's got so much live to give once he gets to know you.  This handsome devil is well worth meeting.  He has not had any successful dog relationships yet, and so far he prefers to be the only furry king of the castle. 
Attachments area

animal.description:
Sherman is the most handsome boy in town! He is happy, loving and eager to please with eyes that will melt your heart. He loves sunbathing in the backyard, barking at himself in the mirror, napping on the couch and playing with his toys. Sherman is going to be a big boy and is still learning how to live in his growing body. He is a bit clumsy and sometimes doesn't realize how big he is. He wants to be a lap dog! He is good with dogs and takes the submissive role and would probably be better in a house with another dog. He loves to play with kids but since he is so young, he is still in a biting phase so probably wouldn't be great with really young kids. He is working on potty training and doing well with consistent trips outside and sleeps through the night in his crate. He can sit and listens well and is a fast learner. He is an amazing guy!

Sherman is a Male Lab / Mastiff Mix that we estimate to be born around 9/8/2020 and currently weighs 30 lbs (as of 1/14/21) but still growing!

If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
FOSTER OR ADOPTER NEEDED!!
 
Meet Popeye... This handsome guy was pulled from the dreaded list at a local shelter a few months ago. A volunteer was hoping to be able to keep him but unfortunately his chair is too much for their other dog with anxiety issues. Popeye is a purebred boxer around 8 years old. He has and old  injury and has neurologic defects in his hind limbs. The good news is that he is continent. He can even get up on his back legs and go without his chair they just are weak and missing a lot of muscle mass. He’s not in pain at all and is the happiest guy! He’s great with all people and other dogs. Sadly, he’s now in boarding at our vet. He does great there but he deserves a home to call his own and treat him like the king he is. He is a super special boy and deserves nothing but the best. Popeye is fully vetted and altered he will also come with his chair if you want it! It’s pink but he loves it! ?

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

ADOPTION APPLICATION

https://form.jotform.us/70898112177159

FOSTER APPLICATION

https://form.jotform.us/71694695237167
